column2:
The deployment POST endpoint does not align with the way that the data is displayed in a number of ways:

1. The jobUrl property is completely ignored (search for references to  DeployDataCreateRequest::getJobUrl() in IDE).  There should be an option to access the job URL component by component.
2. The `appName`/`instanceUrl` property pair is being defined as distinct in the backend [here](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/api/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/service/DeployServiceImpl.java#L242) because the query looks to match the options passed in.  This means that two collectors can be created with the same name, which then appears as the same name in the Deploy widget dropdown.
3. The environmentUrl doesn't get set in the [createEnvComponent](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/api/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/service/DeployServiceImpl.java#L248) method.  This means that jobs submitted by the POST endpoint do not have a functional "View in Jenkins" link, as this is captured by the `environment.url` property [here](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/UI/src/components/widgets/deploy/detail.html#L25)

My suggested solution:
1. `jobUrl` property gets set on the environment_component collection object, then if this value is set it is used by the [deploy detail modal](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/UI/src/components/widgets/deploy/detail.html).  It will need to be at the component level, as the `jobUrl` property is specifying a deploy URL for a component.
2. Make `applicationName` distinct in the CollectorItem repo by removing `option.put("instanceUrl", request.getInstanceUrl());` from [DeployServiceImpl.java](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/api/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/service/DeployServiceImpl.java).  I realize this would be a breaking change for those with duplicate records here already by `applicationName` and `instanceUrl`.  I don't know what the project stance on this issue would be.
3. The `environmentUrl` should be set by the `instanceUrl` that is available in the API object.

I will be creating a PR for the related issues above.  I wanted the issue created to begin a discussion on these solutions.
column5: Deployment API endpoint does not create deployments that display properly
column11:
264688063 Issue 2 becomes especially clear in the code when you look at the `hashCode` and `equals` methods for [`Environment.java`](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/api/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/model/deploy/Environment.java).  The URL is not taken into account when comparing these environments for equality. jmcshane
264971865 > Make applicationName distinct in the CollectorItem repo by removing option.put("instanceUrl", request.getInstanceUrl()); from DeployServiceImpl.java. I realize this would be a breaking change for those with duplicate records here already by applicationName and instanceUrl. I don't know what the project stance on this issue would be.

This will not work in all cases. It is perfectly valid to have the same application name on different instances and these would in turn be different logical items.  MarkRx
264982903 @MarkRx Then the `Environment.java` file needs to change as well as the view for choosing Deployment collectors, as right now the instanceUrl is not included in the display for choosing the collector.  The environment being tested for equality based only on the `appName` property means that I cannot create a map keyed on the `Environment` when there are two records with the same app name.

If you have another solution that allows these multiple instanceUrls in a way that makes it easy to work with, I'm definitely interested in working through this.  We could set a time to discuss on the gitter chat for this project if you are interested. jmcshane
264984105 Let me review this tonight.  tabladrum
264990206 > If you have another solution that allows these multiple instanceUrls in a way that makes it easy to work with, I'm definitely interested in working through this. We could set a time to discuss on the gitter chat for this project if you are interested.

What are you trying to accomplish? If you have the same application spread vertically across different instances (instances meaning deployment tools) look at #891.

In the collector model there is a single collector that defines N number of URLs and niceNames. Each collectorItem refers to the collector and has applicationName, instanceUrl (in options) and 'niceName' set. If the collectorItem has 'niceName' set the UI will differentiate entries using that.

If you send in niceName through the rest endpoint it should differentiate items in the UI for you. Look at https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/891#issuecomment-260472065 for an example. Doing so would allow you to be able to distinguish between two applications with the same name.


 MarkRx

Current Behavior: When the save button is clicked, two different things occur:

1. When no SCM collectors have been configured, I do not see any Console errors in the javascript or in the network requests.  Nothing occurs on the screen.

column5: MongoDB Authentication exception while running api using docker
column11:
264270745 @vishnuvangala 
I also encountered the same issue and solve to follow below steps: 
1. Point mongoDb directory:
    ```
    mongod --dbpath < path to the data directory>
    ```
2. Create database 
    ```
    mongo
    MongoDB shell version: 3.0.4
    connecting to: test  
    > use dashboarddb
    switched to db dashboarddb 
    > db.createUser({
        user: "dashboarduser",
        pwd: "dbpassword",
        roles: [
          { role: "readWrite", db: "dashboard" }
        ]
      })
    ```
    Output similar to below should be seen in your mongo shell
    ```  
    Successfully added user: {
      "user" : "dashboarduser",
      "roles" : [
        {
          "role" : "readWrite",
          "db" : "dashboard"
        }
      ]
    }
    ```
3. Give DB credentials and port properly in you dashboard.properties then
    ```
    java -jar api.jar --spring.config.location=dashboard.properties
    ``` elangesk
264386166 @vishnuvangala @elangesk 
If you use dashboarddb then the role would be
```js
{ role: "readWrite", db: "dashboarddb" }
```
instead of 
```js
{ role: "readWrite", db: "dashboard" } 
```
And the corresponding properties file should have
```properties
dbname=dashboarddb
dbusername=dashboarduser
dbpassword=dbpassword
``` satishc1
264418112 Thanks @elangesk @satishc1 ,
Finally I could resolve this authentication issue but unable to access the api even after starting with below command.. not sure what went wrong.. but able to authenticate successfully with below command... 
But I have a quick question...
In order to setup Hygieia, should I run API, UI and mongoDB mandatorly in docker container? or can I also start with normal commands instead of running in docker container? Please suggest. I see some difficulty while running through docker and even in setting up this HYGIEIA.. if someone could help me in setting up through chat/live.. that would be great.

**Modified command used to run api using docker which resolved the mongo authentication issue:**
```
docker run \
  -t \
  -p 8082:8082 \
  -v /logs:/hygieia/logs \
  -e "SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_HOST=192.168.XX.XXX" \
  -e "SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PORT=27017" \
  -e "SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_DATABASE=dashboarddb" \
  -e "SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_USERNAME=dashboarduser" \
  -e "SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PASSWORD=dbpassword" \
  -i hygieia-api:latest
``` vishnuvangala
264724930 Glad to see your issue is resolved.

Docker is not required in order to run Hygieia - please see the setup instructions for the respective layer of Hygieia that you are trying to run:
https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/Setup.md

ie. for the API layer, you should be able to do:
```bash
mvn install
java -jar api.jar --spring.config.location=dashboard.properties
``` mrpudn

Regards,
Vishnu vishnuvangala

271375821 LGTM tabladrum
264259362 What about all of the collectors? MarkRx
264263826 @MarkRx good question. So as far as the collectors that we're using go, the property that requires encryption is the database password.
Since the API's Docker file defines ENV SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PASSWORD, that is what's been encrypted. This env variable then gets picked up by the other collectors through the docker link to the API via $HYGIEIA_API_ENV_SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PASSWORD.

Let me know if you mean something else. Thanks! Mpluya
264756111 I am very interested in this feature as well and would want it to be available for all Spring Boot apps within the project.  I think with what @Mpluya has provided (with the jasypt library as a core dependency), the `@EnableEncryptableProperties` just needs to be added to each collector.

The argument `jasypt.encryptor.password` can be provided in the `spring.config.location` property file, so it can be called out along with the other configuration parameters in each of the collector `README.md` files.  Then, there would not be a need to have updates to any of the Dockerfiles as it just sits with the other properties. jmcshane
264759834 @Mpluya I created a PR to your project in StateFarmIns to add these properties and a callout in each section of the README documentation, see StateFarmIns/Hygieia#4 jmcshane
264867297 @jmcshane you are correct.  Enabling property encryption on the collectors is just a matter of adding the @EnableEncryptableProperties annotation to the Application class on each collector. I did not add it by default to all the collectors, since I would like property encryption to be added on an as needed basis. I don't want an additional post processor kicking off on startup of each collector if there are no encrypted properties to deal with. I'm open to having it turned on on every collector if thats what we all agree to do. 

As for your pull request, I really appreciate you taking the time to enable property encryption on all collectors. I'd like for folks to weigh in before we put this in. 
As for putting the secret key (jasypt.encryptor.password) as another property, I would have to disagree with this approach. I would prefer for the secret key to be passed in either as a system property or environment variable when starting up your spring boot app. In my opinion, having an encrypted property and next to it is the secret key - pretty much gives away the the decrypted value. That said, in my organization when we startup Hygieia via docker containers, the secret key gets served up from a secure variable in our gitlab ci runner. 

I look forward to hear your thoughts on this. Thank you again. Mpluya
264896583 @Mpluya after thinking this over a little more, you are definitely right about not having the `jasypt.encryptor.password` property in the property file itself.

I think we just need to call this out explicitly in each of the `README.md` files and then, as you say, update the `Dockerfile` for each collector.

I'll make a modification to the PR I sent to remove the callout of the password in the properties and modify the above documentation section to talk about the system property.
 jmcshane

column2:
Currently the Hygieia pipeline is hard coded to use at most 5 stages in the order of DEV > QA > INT > PERF > PROD. We have found that this approach does not satisfy all pipelines. 

I propose the following enhancements:

- (A) Custom stage names with a configurable number of system level stages. Some teams may use more than one level of integration environments. So the pipeline would become DEV > QA > INT1 > INT2 > PERF > PROD
- ~~(B) Configurable order of stages - Some teams use different staging orders. For example PERF testing might come at different locations in the pipeline.~~ System stage groups should be generic enough to work for all teams. I think keeping order consistent will simplify aggregation and metrics a bunch.
- (C) Multiple environments per stage - There may be parallel environments within a stage. For example, suppose there are 3 independent QA environments - qa1, qa2, and qa3. Components may go to any QA in any order. They must go to at least one QA before moving to a higher environment.

(A) is simply a matter of refactoring and adding functionality. (B) and (C) add flexibility at the cost of complexity.

Each team dashboard would be able to define which system level stages to use ~~along with the order that they are used in their pipeline~~. Grouping would also be definable so that N number of environments may be part of the same stage. The UI would have to be updated to display this information.

Product dashboards would have to change to take into account multiple environments per stage. In the case of a team having multiple environments per a stage the earliest date a PipelineCommit is seen in any of the environments in the stage would be used for calculations. 

## Examples
Given a system stage config of DEV, QA, INT1, INT2, PERF, PROD:

| Pipeline | DEV | QA            | INT1 | INT2 | PERF | PROD |
|----------|------|------------|-------|------|-------|--------|
| APP A   | dev1 | qa1 | int-a  | int-main | p1 | prod |
| APP B   | dev1 | qa1 / qa2 | int-a  | int-main | p2 | prod |
| APP C   |         | qa1 |   | int-main | p2 | prod |

Observe that App B has multiple parallel environments defined for the 'QA' stage.

column2:
Hygieia api's log gets stored in ./logs directory whereas the collectors' logs are created in the current directory itself. This inconsistency of log paths is present in src/main/resources/logback.xml

Api's logback.xml:
```xml
<fileNamePattern>logs/devopsdashboard-api-%d{yyyy-MM-dd}.%i.log</fileNamePattern>
```

Jira and other collectors' logback.xml:
```xml
<fileNamePattern>jiracollector-%d{yyyy-MM-dd}.%i.log</fileNamePattern>
```

column2:
Changes:

- Allow for configurable custom artifact formats using regex
- Adds modules, classifiers, and extensions to BinaryArtifacts to make them maven and ivy compliant.
- Artifacts published by jenkins no longer include the file extension as part of the artifact name. Instead the value is stored in the artifactExtension field.

Default artifact formats in documentation:
```
# Matches maven artifacts of the form [org]/[module]/[version]/[module]-[version]([-classifier])(.[ext])
artifactory.patterns[0]=(?<group>.+)/(?<module>[^/]+)/(?<version>[^/]+)/(?<artifact>\\k<module>)-\\k<version>(-(?<classifier>[^\\.]+))?(\\.(?<ext>.+))?
# Matches ivy files of the form [org]/[module]/[revision]/ivy-[revision](-[classifier]).xml 
artifactory.patterns[1]=(?<group>.+)/(?<module>[^/]+)/(?<version>[^/]+)/(?<artifact>ivy)-\\k<version>(-(?<classifier>[^\\.]+))?\\.(?<ext>xml)
# Matches ivy artifact files of the form [org]/[module]/[revision]/[type]/[artifact]-[revision](-[classifier])(.[ext])
artifactory.patterns[2]=(?<group>.+)/(?<module>[^/]+)/(?<version>[^/]+)/(?<type>[^/]+)/(?<artifact>[^\\.-/]+)-\\k<version>(-(?<classifier>[^\\.]+))?(\\.(?<ext>.+))?
```

Notes:

- Jenkins collector does not support maven classifiers at this time

try removing components/ from the end of the server url. If you need to tweak the rest endpoint maybe do it with the artifactory.endpoint property. By default it is 'artifactory/' MarkRx

263569171 The proper rest endpoint for obtaining the list of repositories is defined here: https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/RTF/Artifactory+REST+API#ArtifactoryRESTAPI-GetRepositories

> GET /api/repositories[?type=repositoryType (local|remote|virtual)]

In order to work properly you must be configured such that the URL results in the following:
> http://myurl:8383/api/repositories

Your screenshot has an additional "components" portion in the URL which is incorrect.

```
artifactory.servers[0]=http:/myurl:8383/
artifactory.endpoint=artifactory/
``` MarkRx

column2: Is there any collector to collect data from jenkins auto deploy data. We are using Jenkins for deployment in various stages. We need to collect data and display it in the Deploy widget and Product dashboard view.
column5: Jenkins deploy collector
column11:
263269672 There is not. At present the only way to do this using jenkins is to use a push model and call rest API endpoints to put in deployment data. The jenkins plugin has some functionality to do this. You can also use curl POST calls. MarkRx
263328584 Jenkins being a generic job scheduler, it is difficult to know what the jobs are doing. No way to distinguish between a Jenkins job doing just the build vs say creating a full stack and deploying app. There may be some work arounds (which are not clean) such as having the job names follow certain naming convention etc. Thoughts? tabladrum
263329909 @tabladrum One 'right way' to consider would be to create a Hygieia jenkins plugin that the client adds to thier build as a step, in that plugin we can signal/do whatever we want/need.   jimzucker
263331067 The plugin is already there. We use it.  tabladrum
268545971 @szabbas Use the hygieia jenkins plugin. satishc1

column5: Build broken in Jenkins plugin with java7 due core dependency
column11:
263269266 Hygieia requires java 8. You could always run jenkins with a java 8 runtime and see if it functions properly.

Technically you could make a java 7 build by removing the CommitEventListener class as it seems to be the only item in core that requires java 8 features. No guarantees it will work as dependent libraries may require java 8 as well.
 MarkRx

263350951 If you are using Jenkins for deployments, then we can use the Hygieia Jenkins plugin https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/tree/master/hygieia-jenkins-plugin.

In any case, you can run the curl command from the "server" that runs the deployment job. In your case, it's Jenkins. 

So, you have two options:
1. Use the jenkins plugin
2. Use the curl in Jenkins job's shell command window. tabladrum

column2:
Contains a number of jira and feature collector / widget changes rolled up into a single PR from @pxk5958 

Changes:

- Jira collector now supports gathering team data. In the past Jira projects were being placed into 'scope' and 'ScopeOwner' (in collector_items). Now if the tempo team field is configured in the collector the team data is placed in 'ScopeOwner'. 
- Feature widget can filter based on project name, team name, or both. To grab all items for a given field / team the 'Any' option can be selected in the drop down.
- Feature widget can be configured to list Epics (previously called 'features') or Issues (stories, defects, spikes, etc).
- Added hyperlinks to epics / issues in progress
- Added hyperlink to sprint in progress
- Issues that have been completed now have a strikethrough on the UI
- Issues are sorted by modified date. Epics are still sorted by points. We feel that when listing stories a user will be more interested in recent activity.
- Feature widget modified to display open / in progress / done estimate metrics instead of total / in progress / done as this seems to be more intuitive.
- Added the ability to collect data on multiple issues types in the Jira collector
- Improved documentation / configuration of jira collector - renamed 'feature.jiraIssueTypeId' to 'feature.jiraIssueTypeNames'

Note: the feature collection will have to be wiped / reset in order to take advantage of urls and teams

The jira collector items that correspond to scopeowners will have to be wiped as they currently store project information

@tabladrum @amitmawkin we need to know how to construct urls to versionone assets in order to have hyperlinks be available for the version one feature.

![feature2](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/17504314/20573965/545aca3a-b180-11e6-9e9f-6423b1681e5c.png)

Based on that section of the stack trace, my guess is you didn't include a cron sequence in your properties file, or an invalid one.  Makes sure you having something like the line below in your application properties file.  
`gitlab.cron=0 0/1 * * * *` rob-miller-777

gitlab.properties file:

dbname=dashboarddb

gitlab.saveLog=true

gitlab jar Command:

263285435 Think you are now at the same point as #957 , I will be working on a fix for that this week.  Your properties file does need to be updated however.  Server, branche, and saveLog are no longer properties.  Instead use the properties below.  I will be adding two new properties for port and protocol to support the issue in 957.  

```properties
gitlab.cron=0 0/3 * * * *
gitlab.apiToken={token}
gitlab.host={host}
gitlab.selfSignedCertificate=false
gitlab.commitThresholdDays=15
``` rob-miller-777

column2:
Our organization has a requirement to not store credentials (i.e. database credentials) in plaintext on the property files.
I noticed the codebase already has support for encrypt/decrypt by using the Encryption class on the core project.
The only downside in my opinion is I now have to add code to call the encryption class. It would be nice if my encypted properties are served up automatically decrypted.
That said, I found jasypt-spring-boot (Jasypt integration for Spring boot). It boot straps a Spring post processor which makes the app aware of the encrypted properties. Details about jasypt-spring-boot is here https://github.com/ulisesbocchio/jasypt-spring-boot.




My question is, would there be any interest in incorporating this in Hygieia?

column2:
Currently the Hygieia product allows users to create accounts, and then stores the passwords to those accounts in Mongo. This PR adds a new authentication service that can be used for LDAP based authentication to gain access to Hygieia. It uses an existing LDAP server implemeted by the deploying organization to check if an account merely exists. It has not been tested against group level access, but by modifying the dn in the application.properties file, more fine-grain restrictions should be able to be enforced (see README).

LDAP authentication can be activated through the "ldapAuth" spring profile, and setup instructions have been added to the api README.
column5: Ldap integration2

How does one turn this on or off using configuration in the docker files and docker-compose?
 MarkRx
261376738 I was unaware of there being admin functionality without these changes. Based on that assumption, this was not designed to support admin users.
To run with LDAP, the Dockerfile CMD for the API would be changed to say
`java -jar ....... --spring.profiles.active=ldapAuth` 

Running without LDAP is the default behavior.

261382466 @brennanananan undocumented feature, if you create a user with name admin you get to see an extra gear on the right top hand corner  that allows you to delete any dashboard and set themes.
 amitmawkin
261384839 Thanks @amitmawkin , I will take a look at how to incorporate that feature into my changes. Does the admin 'group' only get those two extra actions?
 brennanananan
261411293 Also, it seems you're assuming the usernames will be stored under uid. It may not be so and needs to be configurable as a search filter.

[Referrals](http://docs.oracle.com/javase/jndi/tutorial/ldap/referral/jndi.html) also need to be handled.

I encountered these issues with my organization's LDAP when working on this.
 pxk5958
261556709 - You need to change the docker properties builder so that no rebuild is necessary to be able to use LDAP
- The "sign up" feature needs to be hidden if ldap is enabled
- The "sign up" api call needs to throw an exception if ldap is enabled
- I would prefer reusing the existing auth controller and just checking a property dynamically to see if LDAP is enabled instead of using a spring profile. You can stick it into the systemConfig property map for now that is part of API. In the future we may want to build a System Config UI that can change these values and store them into the database. Using spring profiles prevents dynamic property changes without a restart.
- For now as a work around if the username is "admin" log in using the old mechanism. If not use ldap. A admin entry would have to be created in the database manually since the signup will be disabled if ldap is enabled (or create the admin user first then disable ldap). User roles could be added in the future.
 MarkRx

column2:
Currently Does not support Proxy configuration - For Proxy add the -D flags while starting API.
This is still debatable whether we should save proxy credentials in Hygieia. We are discussing more internally before we enable proxy configuration.

Also currently the duration on which the API's are tested is every minute, in future we will make this configurable too.

More details about this can be read from features.md file.

This is still a WIP, we will be adding some more configuration and capabilities to this

In features.md:

> +###Basic Http Monitoring###
> - Hygieia Monitoring widget now supports basic http monitoring.
> - 
> - 
> - To use this feature use the CapOne template. The widget is very simple to configure, you just need to add the url of the services you need to monitor in the format and provide a friendly name to it.
> - The widget also supports listing dependent services and monitoring them. So if a dependent services is already configured on a another dashboard you can just declare them as dependent services.
> - 
> - `http://samplewebsite.com or https://samplewebsite.com`
> - 
> - Please do remember that if you are using a self signed certificate you would run into following error
> - 
> - `2016-11-14 17:08:25,452 ERROR c.c.d.service.ServiceServiceImpl - https://abc1234.com failed with sun.security.validator.ValidatorException: PKIX path building failed: sun.security.provider.certpath.SunCertPathBuilderException: unable to find valid certification path to requested target`
> - 
> - to resolve this please import the certificate into the JVM running your api using java keytool. 
> - 
> - Also at this time, the monitoring widget does not supports any proxy configuration.
>   Why not? Setting up proxy config is pretty straight forward
 amitmawkin

column2:
My company uses Jira with four different states: Blocked, To Do, In Progress, and Done. 
With the way that the feature widget is implemented, there are a lot of changes that must be made to display all 4 queues. Has anyone made modifications like this?
column5: Customizable States for Feature / Jira Widget
column11:
259968101 Internally jira has 3 non-modifiable categories: open, in progress, and done. This is the way jira works. Versionone appears to be the same. Your company must of mapped "blocked" to one of those types. The existing feature widget / collectors are modeled around this assumption so adding a fourth category would be a large change.
 MarkRx

column2:
In Pipeline Health Trends we find Arrows(Up & Down) followed by percentage values. Could you please explain the purpose of Up and Down arrows and it's colors.

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/835620/20137524/fe78a16c-a6a0-11e6-8f35-619da19fcc53.png)
column5: explain the purpose of Pipeline Health Trends Up or Down arrows
column11:
260465909 The arrows are for showing trend. Up is going high. Down is going low. Some UPs are bad and hence colored red. Some DOWNs are good and hence colored green..
Green = good. Red = bad. Up = trending up in value (% or count etc). Down = trending down.

column2:
**Bug Fixes:**

- Removed unused code/commented code
- Now filter by collector id when retrieving collectors
- Actually use branch provided by user
- Removed unused application settings 
- Set number of changes on a commit to 1 instead of 159753
- Utilized rest operations class instead of building an Http request 

**Enhancements:**

- Not utilizes Gitlab host set in application properties
- Extracted Url Building logic into a utility class
- Extracted building of Commit object from json string into a mapper class
- Limit number of commits returned to last 14 days
- Utilized clean method from github collector instead of just wiping everything out each time
- Get commits for branch instead of all
- Can now choose branch from UI instead of props file
- Utilize Spring URI Builder to manage url building instead of string manipulation
- Added support for Gitlab's pagination
- Moved API token into the header instead of the Url
- Added ability to provide API Token for private repos
- Added Unit Tests
- Added optional settings for trusting self signed certificates

column2:
Sonar Web Service API has a hardcoded limit of 500 results for "api/resources" call. As a result Sonar collector won't fetch all projects if there are more than 500.

See Sonar Jira issue for  this:
https://jira.sonarsource.com/browse/SONAR-2920
column5: Sonar Collector not retrieving more than 500 projects

column2:
The existing repository tests in the core module utilize the [flapdoodle](https://github.com/flapdoodle-oss/de.flapdoodle.embed.mongo) mongo plugin to download and run a mongodb instance when the repository unit tests are executed. To prevent a workstation from connecting to the Internet to download and "install" software, these tests have been refactored to utilize [fongo](https://github.com/fakemongo/fongo).

Fongo is an in-memory implementation of mongodb, it intercepts calls to the mongodb drivers. It is pulled down as a maven dependency, thus no runtime downloading/installation of packages.

The intention of the repository tests feels the same with this change.

Thanks!

column2:
Adds ability to configure a regular expression to indicate environments that can ignore errors. If an environment ignores errors the UI will use a gray icon instead of a red one. The deploy widget will only turn red if an environment that is not ignoring errors fails.

Use case: There are cases when we don't care if an environment is down. In a blue/green stage-active deployment we never care about the "staging" environment. Without this change the deploy widget will almost always be red (as usually no code is staged).

** Update **
Configuration is specified in the deploy widget config

Requires PR #891 

![taxsdlc666-1](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/17504314/19867131/4af8391e-9f79-11e6-8c4e-778a7c159fac.PNG)

Update: Added additional ability to configure on a per dashboard basis.
![taxsdlc666-4](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/17504314/20807235/1758e0fc-b7cc-11e6-8dd0-65c4821df199.PNG)

256417480 Followed below steps for encryption

Encryption for private repos

From module core generate a secret key. java -jar /core-2.0.2-SNAPSHOT.jar com.capitalone.dashboard.util.Encryption
Add this generated key to api.properties ### api.properties key=
Add the same key to your repo settings file. This is needed for the target collector to decrypt your saved repo password. For example, if your repo is github add the following. ### github.properties github.key=

column2:
Pulls maven and ivy artifacts from JFrog artifactory. Can handle multiple artifactory instances At present assumes the following artifact patterns:

> - 1. Maven artifacts:
> -      [org]/[module]/[version]/[module]-[version][-classifier].[ext]
> - 2. Ivy artifacts:
> -      (a) [org]/[module]/[revision]/[type]/[artifact]-[revision](-[classifier]).[ext]
> -      (b) [org]/[module]/[revision]/ivy-[revision](-[classifier]).xml

Known Issues:
- Cannot pull in updates on artifacts when only properties are updated. This is due to a limitation on the JFrog artifactory rest API.

@pxk5958

256064213 The `mongo` shell is actually a JavaScript shell, so you can do things like:

``` js
> var users = db.authentication.find()

// print the first user
> users[0]

// print the user count:

```

Based on the suggestion referenced the UI readme file section in the Encryption for private repos

Following the below step have generated a secret key and updated the respective properties file. Look like this also did not help..

From module core generate a secret key.

``` bash
java -jar /core-2.0.2-SNAPSHOT.jar com.capitalone.dashboard.util.Encryption
```

Add this generated key to api.properties

``` properties
    key=

    Add the same key to your repo settings file.
    This is needed for the target collector to decrypt your saved repo password.
    For example, if your repo is github add the following.
    github.properties

    github.key=
```

column2:
Fix for #678. Backwards compatible. Adds the ability to configure a widget to interpret sprints as either kanban, scrum, or both. This is necessary since it is not possible to deduce which sprint type a project uses from the rest api. I also did some code cleanup while there. The basic issue with the current code is that it interpreted features without sprints as being KANBAN which is not true in all use cases.

Here is how it works:
In order to be considered part of the sprint the feature must not be deleted and must have an "active" sprint asset state if the sprint is set. The following logic also applies:

A feature is part of a scrum sprint if any of the following are true:
- the feature has a sprint set that has start <= now <= end and end < EOT (9999-12-31T59:59:59.999999)

A feature is part of a kanban sprint if any of the following are true:
- the feature does not have a sprint set
- the feature has a sprint set that does not have an end date
- the feature has a sprint set that has an end date >= EOT (9999-12-31T59:59:59.999999)

Note the above are mutually exclusive.

Observe how this handles all of the following use cases:
- Typical scrums (a sprint is live for X number of weeks)
- Kanban without any sprints assigned
- Kanban using a sprint without an end date
- Kanban that was set from previous code that interpretted not having a sprint set as being KANBAN (since we use EOT in the queries above)
- Scrum & Kanban (don't see how this is a real world use case but it works similar to the previous code. Kanban will interpret backlog items as being part of kanban but that issue is existing and cannot be resolved due to lack of information)
- The code in the versionone widget that interprets sprints that have an end date > some cutoff as being KANBAN. This works as it will not end up setting the sprint data which causes the feature to be interpreted as kanban

@amp5208 @tabladrum

column11:
254196740 I see a TimeoutException and seeing that you have over 1000 projects I would image there are a lot of user stories. 

Here are a few things you could try:
- Double check this property. It should be a string despite its name. It needs to be renamed:
  > feature.jiraIssueTypeId=Story
- Decrease the page size
- See if you can get a response using http REST. Example: 
  > curl -u username:password "https://jira.instance.com/rest/api/2/search?jql=updatedDate%3E%3D%272016-08-01%2019%3A23%27%20AND%20issueType%3D%27Story%27%20ORDER%20BY%20updated%20ASC&fields=*all%2C-comment%2C-watches%2C-worklog%2C-votes%2C-reporter%2C-creator%2C-attachment&maxResults=200&startAt=0"
- See if someone could do some database turning in jira to improve query response time
- Check for network issues
 MarkRx
254208227 @oshingc @MarkRx  
Another suggestion for 
org.apache.http.nio.reactor.ssl.SSLIOSession.receiveEncryptedData(SSLIOSession.java:340) ~

Is your jira using a self-signed SSL cert ? Check if your logs have any SSL cert exceptions. Try starting up the jira collector with -Djavax.net.ssl.trustStore=<yourtruststore> where <yourtruststore> is file containing the public key of your cert.
Refer https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/335

252785510 @preetcam 
For the UI module set the proxypass directive in apache to point to wherever your api module is running.

ProxyPass /api http://localhost:8080/api

To find out where the api module is running ...
If you have logging set, you should see something like the following line when the api module is started up.
2016-10-07 15:20:29,037 INFO  o.s.b.c.e.t.TomcatEmbeddedServletContainer - Tomcat initialized with port(s): 8080 (http)

The above line will tell you the port number that the api runs on. Test it with the ping api..
http://localhost:8080/api/ping
 satishc1
253285507 Thanks it works !!

column2:
This change allows the deployment widgets to handle more than one server. It has a configuration that can be set to allow this.

Use case: We have multiple deployment servers that are split up by function. One handles prod and prod-like environments. The other handles test, qa, and dev environments. Data gathered from multiple servers needs to be correlated together and treated as one application.

Changes:
- API now supports multiple deployment collectors per a single dashboard
- UI has ability to correlate applications together by ID (when enabled) thus allowing multiple deployment collector items to be used under the hood.
- Add API + UI configurable options ( #890 )

Changes will work with existing documents in the database.
column5: Handling multiple cross functional deployment servers

column2:
Is there a place where global system configurations live? The UI has the ability to configure themes but it doesn't seem this data is persisted.

I have a use case where I have a configuration that might effect multiple images (ui, api, and collectors). I need someplace common to store the configuration.
column5: Global configuration?
column11:
252545983 I always thought there should be a `/config` directory at the top-level of the project, which would contain all configuration for Hygieia.

There should be a `.dist` version for each config file (ex. `api.properties.dist`), which would be the "distributable" version of the configuration. You'd copy the dist version and remove the `.dist` to apply your custom configurations (ex. `api.properties`) - these would all be `.gitignore`ed.

I'd rather have all configuration in one file (`hygieia.properties`), but I'm not sure how everyone would feel about that.

Thoughts?
 mrpudn
254901779 How would that work when using docker? I wouldn't want properties to be handled at compile time.

I think for now I'm going to look into creating a rest service on the api that returns a bunch of configuration options that the UI makes use of when deciding how to render the views. The properties would be set in the api's application.properties file. The config is still static (needs to be compiled before running) but I'm not sure it would make sense for those properties that I mentioned in my use case to be dynamically configurable.
 MarkRx
254930427 Yeah configuring docker containers is a little more complicated.. like you said, ideally configuration would be done at runtime, not compile time, so that you can have a generic image with specific configuration.
 mrpudn
256093245 Threw in config skeleton as part of #891
 MarkRx
298363751 Closing. MarkRx
252279135 Examples:
- allowScmCredentials - if the UI should show the username/password fields for SCM
- allowAccountCreation - if account creation is allowed (for future LDAP hookup)
- globalTheme - the global theme
 MarkRx

column2:
This PR adds a dynamic product dashboard pipeline service that can be enabled with the feature.dynamicPipeline=enabled feature switch. This requires PR #815. More details in comment https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/804#issuecomment-247391585.

Basically data for commits, builds, deployments, and artifacts are associated dynamically using constructed composite keys. That correlated data is calculated on-demand. Doing so solves a number of synchronization issues that are pointed out below.

Data is correlated in the following ways: 
- Build -> Commit: Builds keep track of the SCM revision numbers as well as the repository and branch information (though builds with multiple repositories are not 100% accurate). Given a list of commits for the dashboard we can correlate builds to them using the scm revision number.
- EnvironmentComponent -> BinaryArtifact: Given a list of Environments we can gather DeploymentUnits and associate them to BinaryArtifacts by the component name and version number. In the future this information may be stored in metadata that is retrieved by the deployment collector. 
- BinaryArtifact -> Commit: An artifact will contain information about the HEAD svn revision number that was used to produce it. Given the scm revision number we can find it in our list of commits that are tracked for the dashboard and determine it along with all previous commits. For GIT this is done using a graph built from Commit.getScmParentRevisionNumbers(). For SVN we simply grab all revisions with a number less than ours.

This addresses the following issues
- #816 - Deploying old applications does not properly reflect in the product dashboard: only commits that come prior to the head commit for the version that was deployed are used
- #828 - Bug: Commits in the pipeline only show up in the last configured environment: since the EnvironmentComponent event listener doesn't play in to this this bug doesn't get hit
- #804 - Pipeline document not preemptively filled when created: pipeline is generated with each call
- #810 - NPE in CommitEventListener (bitbucket collector): partially fixed while I was in the code (no NPE)
- #869 - Bug: pipeline dashboard build commit time statistics off: fixed this while I was in the code
- #806 - Publishing artifacts requires build information to have already been collected: Fixed by PR #815

Sample artifact document:

```
{
    "_id" : ObjectId("57f2680746e0fb000e3026fc"),
    "_class" : "com.capitalone.dashboard.model.BinaryArtifact",
    "timestamp" : NumberLong(1475504135011),
    "artifactName" : "Helloworld",
    "canonicalName" : "Helloworld",
    "artifactGroupId" : "com.paychex.helloworld",
    "artifactVersion" : "4.9.7.20161003-101416I",
    "metadata" : {
        "jobName" : "mrichar2_helloworld",
        "scmUrl" : "https://repo.com/scm/~username/helloworld.git",
        "scmBranch" : "master",
        "buildUrl" : "http://jenkins.instance.com/job/helloworld/235/",
        "jobUrl" : "http://jenkins.instance.com/job/helloworld/",
        "buildNumber" : "235",
        "scmRevisionNumber" : "bea69104639e87faff235827e036e5021d1f93cf",
        "instanceUrl" : "http://jenkins.instance.com/"
    }
}
```

Note the following limitations / items not implemented at this time:
- Dynamic pipeline does not currently support SVN
- Date bounding is ignored as there is a current defect in the UI that shows itself here
- Only handles 1 component (though this is the same with the existing pipeline implementation)
- Jenkins branches are not 100% reliable - #857 - code currently does not filter on branch. We can get away with it for now due to commits already being filtered by branch. See comment in DynamicPipelineServiceImpl.filterBuilds for more info.
- Data doesn't display right away. This is an existing issue - #864. To work around open and close the options panel
- Jenkins commits sometimes get missed by builds. This is existing and occours with the event listener implementation as well. To work around it older commits that get skipped are added back using our best guess for a timestamp. This is a similar approach to what the BuildEventListener does
- Performance for very large datasets is not known. I don't think it will be a problem since it should be about on par with the amount of time to load team dashboards since it uses the same service calls
- Branch equality needs to be made smarter. Jenkins will use 'origin/master' whereas the user might only use 'master'

 satishc1
255064045 Based on one of the suggestion referenced the UI readme file section in the  Encryption for private repos

Following the below step have generated a secret key and updated the respective properties file. Look like this also did not help..
1. From module core generate a secret key.
   
   ``` bash
   java -jar <path-to-jar>/core-2.0.2-SNAPSHOT.jar com.capitalone.dashboard.util.Encryption
   ```
2. Add this generated key to api.properties
   
   ``` properties
   ### api.properties
   key=<your-generated-key>
   ```
3. Add the same key to your repo settings file.
   This is needed for the target collector to decrypt your saved repo password.
   For example, if your repo is github add the following.
   
   ``` properties
   ### github.properties
   github.key=<your-generated-key>
   ```

column2:
Spring boot tokenization works only for properties bundles inside the spring boot jar. To cater to this and preserve backwards compatibility.
- Introduced a new file called version.properties
- File gets updated by maven during build phase with current version.
- The property value is injected in the class requiring this.

column5: CollectorTaskTests failing
column11:
249667571 Found it.

So the test is written to verify that save is called with the instance c one time.
`verify(baseCollectorRepository, times(1)).save(c);`

Save is called twice each with different instances. What is probably desired is checking that save is called twice using Mockito.any(Collector.class).

My failure is due to adding hashcode and equals to the BaseModel that is based on the ObjectId. When running junits the ObjectId is null so Collectors have the same hashcode and are equal. As a result it appears that save (c) is called twice since each invocation equality check works out.
 MarkRx

column2:
BuildEventListener.java is using build.getTimestamp() for the PipelineCommit timestamps. The timestamp on builds is being stamped with the system time of when the collector was run. Hence when the collector first runs and picks up a lot of builds these builds will have nearly identical timestamps. The pipeline will then report numbers based on these timestamps (when the collector ran as opposed to when the build ran).

The code should instead reference build.getStartTime() (or build.getEndTime()) to more accurately represent when the commit entered that stage of the pipeline.

Add troubleshooting section to readme to address any existing duplicate dashboard titles.

https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/812 was fixed by adding a unique index to the title field in the dashboards collection. 

But If there happen to be any duplicate titles already existing in the database, the api module will fail to launch with the following error :
Error creating bean with name 'dashboardRepository': Invocation of init method failed; nested exception is org.springframework.dao.DuplicateKeyException: Write failed with error code 11000 and error message 'null'.

This problem can be fixed by running the fixdups.js file on the mongodb instance as mentioned in the readme.

column2: - Have jenkins pull branch information if available
column5: Change jenkins collector to pull scm branch information
column11:
256919007 @tabladrum lets not support multi repository, nothing good comes out of it.
 amitmawkin
256927515 I agree with @amitmawkin. I've conversed a lot with @pxk5958 and we came to the same conclusion. The "multi-repository" functionality for the git plugin is broken and unreliable. Even if it worked as intended its use case is questionable at best. The maintainers agree. They suggest using the multi-scm plugin for multiple git repos. The code changes @pxk5958 will work for multi-scm.
 MarkRx
256929748 LGTM
 amitmawkin
258135444 Ok. I am good with not supporting multi repository. Can we think of a way to put a big bold disclaimer or something? 
 tabladrum
258135869 LGTM
 tabladrum
248899364 There are few ways this might fail. One such can be this situation:
1. Setup Jenkins job with two git repo (not using MultiSCM plugin). Commit to both and you will notice that there are two back to back Jenkins builds - for each repo changes. See if your code can match the right branch.
2. If there are multiple commits in a single build, the branch refers to the top level commit. In a build with changes to multiple git repos (using Multi SCM plugin), there is no simple way to match the branch - unless we assume certain formatting to be true: origin refers to repo[0], origin1 refers to repo[1] etc.
 tabladrum
248918607 @pxk5958 could you take a look?
 MarkRx
249019343 @tabladrum Thanks. I am looking into the various cases.
 pxk5958
251985289 What we are going to do is given the branch information and the originX number we can determine the remoteUrl by pulling the job config that was used for the build and correlating the X to the X'th repo. 

It turns out that the "remoteUrls" list is buggy to begin with so this should be more reliable. I found a case where I specified multiple repositories but it ended up building one of them and claiming it built the other one.
 MarkRx
253910170 There are 2 cases to consider here.
1. Multiple repositories configured through Jenkins MultiSCM plugin. 
   In this case, each remoteUrl is in a separate action in the json response, so we just have to iterate over the actions and find the remoteUrl and corresponding branch in the lastBuiltRevision of each action. 
2. Multiple repositories configured through the 'Add repository' button on the Jenkins Git plugin.
   In this case, the remoteUrls are together in the same action and are not necessarily in the correct order to associate the remote origin, origin1, origin2,...,origin[n] with the corresponding url. There are 2 ways to go about solving this:
   (a) Parse the jenkins job config.xml and find out the remoteUrls in order. There are 2 drawbacks to this approach. If the config.xml file was changed in the time between when a job is triggered and before the queued job finally executes, we cannot get the right config.xml since we don't have the information as to when exactly the job was triggered (as opposed to when it was executed which is available in the json). The other drawback is that if the repository url is parameterized in the config, we won't have the correct url as well.
   (b) Jenkins Git plugin currently stores the remoteUrls in a HashSet which is why they are unordered. I modified it to a LinkedHashSet so that we can get them ordered and hence associate with the correct branch. I have raised an issue (https://issues.jenkins-ci.org/browse/JENKINS-38800) and have submitted a pull request with this change (https://github.com/jenkinsci/git-plugin/pull/441) but the maintainer doesn't see so far why we would need to configure multiple repositories.
   Also, like @MarkRx mentioned, sometimes the build information is wrong when multiple repositories are configured in the Git plugin, but it happens only if we change the job configuration by adding more repositories after at least 1 build has already been done. In other words, results are consistent as long as we never add more repositories after a job has been created and executed at least once.

Considering these, I think we should drop support for multiple repositories in Git plugin since it seems buggy but should support adding branch information for single repositories and MultiSCM plugin. What do you think? @tabladrum 
 pxk5958
256919007 @tabladrum lets not support multi repository, nothing good comes out of it.
 amitmawkin
256927515 I agree with @amitmawkin. I've conversed a lot with @pxk5958 and we came to the same conclusion. The "multi-repository" functionality for the git plugin is broken and unreliable. Even if it worked as intended its use case is questionable at best. The maintainers agree. They suggest using the multi-scm plugin for multiple git repos. The code changes @pxk5958 will work for multi-scm.
 MarkRx

304008932 @HygieiaUser  - install hygieia-jenkins publisher plugin and configure post build actions in your jenkins jobs for all environments. Plugin will push deployment data to Mongo and deploy widget in you dashboard will display your job names. Follow https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/tree/master/hygieia-jenkins-plugin
Once deploy widget is configured, configure pipeline widget and then you should see all the information on product dashboard.  nireeshT

249586861 The documentation in the docker yml file indicates that JIRA_ISSUE_TYPE_ID should be set to the ID of the User Story or Epic IssueType. However, in StoryDataClientImpl.java at line 194 it reads that value into a String issueTypeName, then compares each jira's issue type name against that ID. It never processes feature/sprint/assignee data in the loop. I found this in 2.0.2, but appears to be the same in master.
Changing line 210 to compare against issueType.getId() fixes the problem and jira data appears in the widget.

column5: docker image for UI layer
column11:
248535280 Try:

``` bash
sudo docker run -d \
  -p 8088:80 \
  --name hygieia-ui \
  --link hygieia-api \
  -i hygieia-ui:latest
```

The `-d` flag should run the container in daemon mode, so the terminal should give you back your shell session.

Jenkins collector overrides the hostname setting in application.properties and defaults to localhost. As a result it fails to connect to Jenkins host for accessing build info with api calls.

application.properties

```
# Database Name
dbname=dashboard
# Database HostName - default is localhost
dbhost=localhost
# Database Port - default is 27017
dbport=27017
# Database Username - default is blank
dbusername=dashboarduser
# Database Password - default is blank
dbpassword=dbpassword

# Collector schedule (required)
jenkins.cron=0 0/5 * * * *
jenkins.servers[0]=http://jenkinshost:8989
```

Error from collector logs below

```
2016-09-16 15:05:01,171 ERROR c.c.d.collector.DefaultHudsonClient - Client exception loading build details: I/O error on GET request for "http://localhost:8989/job/testbuild/24/api/json?tree=number,url,timestamp,duration,building,result,culprits[fullName],changeSet[items[user,author[fullName],revision,id,msg,timestamp,date,paths[file]],kind,revisions[module,revision]],actions[lastBuiltRevision[SHA1,branch[SHA1,name]],remoteUrls]":Connection refused: connect; nested exception is java.net.ConnectException: Connection refused: connect. URL =http://localhost:8989/job/testbuild/24/
```

Any clue to resolve ?

247588057 You want to set JIRA_BASE_URL to your JIRA server, to get lira to work you actually want to set all of these variables to the correct value for you instance. if you are using the docker compose you can put this entry with modified values in docker-compose.override.yml.

hygieia-jira-feature-collector:
  environment:
- JIRA_BASE_URL=https://stratengllc.atlassian.net/
- JIRA_CREDENTIALS=xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
- JIRA_ISSUE_TYPE_ID=10200
- JIRA_SPRINT_DATA_FIELD_NAME=customfield_10007
- JIRA_EPIC_FIELD_NAME=customfield_10008
 jimzucker
247925988 I am facing issues with Jenkins collector. Jenkins collector defaults to localhost always causing failures in api request to jenkin host.

Please suggest.
 bjayagop
248079517 As @jimzucker said:

> > You want to set JIRA_BASE_URL to your JIRA server

You'll have to edit your `.properties` file for the JIRA collector to point to your server
 mrpudn
250430818 How is JIRA_BASE_URL related to Jenkins collector ? The issue is in Jenkins collector and NOT in JIRA.

Pls suggest.
 bjayagop
250493719 Oh, sorry - sometimes all of this stuff just blends together, haha.

Are you running the collector in docker? It looks like there's a few things that might be the culprit
 mrpudn
277297968 @bjayagop You might be missing this --spring.config.name=jenkins while you are running the jenkins collector .. or you might have set it to hudson.  Reopen if still an issue. satishc1

column2:
Hi, We are trying to use Hygieia dashboard with SVN for first time.So do not have much idea, hence this might a stupid question:
Q: Based on the details that we have in DB for SVN, can we configure anything in Hygieia to send mails for  SVN details as report.
Or please let me know if we have any script available separately that we use to get the details and send the report.
Thanks !
-Akhilesh
column5: Is Email functionality can be integrated with Hygieia?
column11: 286209777 @AkhileshKJ You could do an svn post-commit hook to send an email and provide the hygieia dashboard url within it. You could add email functionality within hygieia by changing some code in the svn collector, but you would need to think about what causes the email to be triggered. satishc1

I am here stuck with some unknown issues, which is still blocking me with the finalization. As a reference I am pasting my docker file and properties-builder file:

> 
**> PROPERTIES-BUILDER**
> 				
> 				
> 				
> 				
> #!/bin/bash
> # if we are linked, use that info
> if [ "$MONGO_PORT" != "" ]; then
>   # Sample: MONGO_PORT=tcp://172.17.0.20:27017
>   export SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_HOST=`echo $MONGO_PORT|sed 's;.*://\([^:]*\):\(.*\);\1;'`
>   export SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PORT=`echo $MONGO_PORT|sed 's;.*://\([^:]*\):\(.*\);\2;'`
> fi
> 
> echo "SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_HOST: $SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_HOST"
> echo "SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PORT: $SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PORT"
> 
> 
> cat > dashboard.properties <<EOF
> #Database Name - default is test
> dbname=${SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_DATABASE:-dashboarddb}
> 
> #Database HostName - default is localhost
> dbhost=127.0.0.1
> 
> #Database Port - default is 27017
> dbport=27017
> 
> #Database Username - default is blank
> dbusername=dashboarduser
> 
> #Database Password - default is blank
> dbpassword=dbpassword
> 
> feature.dynamicPipeline=${FEATURE_DYNAMIC_PIPELINE:-disabled}
> EOF
> 
> 
> 
> 
> ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
> 
> 
**> DOCKER File**
> 
> 
> 
> FROM docker.io/java:openjdk-8-jdk
> 
> MAINTAINER Hygieia@capitalone.com
> 
> 
> ENV SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_DATABASE=dashboarddb
> ENV SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_HOST=127.0.0.1
> ENV SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PORT=27017
> ENV SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_USERNAME=dashboarduser
> ENV SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PASSWORD=dbpassword
> 
> 
> RUN \
>   mkdir /hygieia
> 
> COPY hygieia /hygieia
> COPY properties-builder.sh /hygieia/
> 
> 
> WORKDIR /hygieia
> 
> VOLUME ["/hygieia/logs"]
> 
> 
> EXPOSE 8080
> CMD sh properties-builder.sh &&\
>   java -Djava.security.egd=file:/dev/./urandom -jar api.jar --spring.config.location=C:/Abhishek/nn/Hygieia/api/dashboard.properties
>   
>   RUN sed -i -e 's/\r$//' ./properties-builder.sh


I would really appreciate your kind help in letting me know the possible reasons and the some suggestions to overcome.

Thanks and regards,
Abhishek Saxena abhishekdgenious

248199498 This might not solve your problem, but it's worth a shot ðŸ˜ƒ 

You should be able to run any module like this, too:

``` bash
mvn spring-boot:run \
  -pl <project> \
  -Dspring.config.location=<path>
# example:
mvn spring-boot:run \
  -pl collectors/build/jenkins-cucumber \
  -Dspring.config.location=config/jenkins-cucumber.properties
```

(I should probably document this somewhere haha)

I'm not really familiar with the Jenkins Cucumber collector, but if you need to pass JVM args in, you can do that with the usual `-D...` prefixed args.

Note that the parent revision data will only come from the commit collectors. Hence at present commits in the pipeline document for build and environments will not contain the parent scm revision number information.

column2:
A concept of "component" is used throughout Hygieia, especially in the context of deployments. For example, environment_component collection associates environment data to "components". Component.java has this:

> /**
> - A self-contained, independently deployable piece of the larger application. Each component of an application
> - has a different source repo, build job, deploy job, etc.
>   *
>   */

So here is my question: which of the two scenario's best illustrates a component?
Suppose I have an application with two parts that come from two wars: myapp-api.war and myapp-ui.war. These are deployed together. For the sake of argument suppose they are built separately and come from separate repositories.
1. **Components live at the artifact level**. They are what comes out of builds. Both myapp-api.war and myapp-ui.war are components. They happen to be deployed together.
2. **Components live at the deployment level**. They consist of a collection of artifacts. In this example my component is a deployment package that consists of myapp-api.war and myapp-ui.war. They are always deployed together.

I've been assuming that number 2 is the definition that is being used - namely tracking deployment packages as opposed to individual artifacts. However, it doesn't appear that Hygieia is setup to handle this situation the way I devised it. In particular, the product dashboard can only watch 1 artifact from 1 build that comes from 1 repository. The scenario I setup has 1 component : 2 builds : 2 repositories.
column5: Definition of "Component"?
column11: 433925402 A component is a generic place holder in Hygieia. It may or may not be tied to a single or multiple artifact. It is there just to allow future growth. tabladrum

column2: If an older version of a component is deployed it will not be reflected properly in the product dashboard. This is because the EnvironmentComponentEventListener always adds the commits from the builds from the latest artifacts. There is no logic to remove commits. Thus if an older version is deployed into an environment newer commits will still exist in the pipeline document resulting in an inaccurate dashboard.
column5: Deploying old applications does not properly reflect in the product dashboard

247392610 Please send me your contact info to my work email: tapabrata.pal@capitalone.com. I will put something on the calendar.
 tabladrum
247000205 Here is a potential solution:
1. Artifacts need to store information about the scmRevisionNumber, scmUrl, and scmBranch that was used to create them. For a MVP we should assume an artifact comes from one repository.
2. Commits need to store information to allow a graph to be built in memory. A commit can store its parent commits (more than one for merges). A graph can be built in memory based on the HEAD information from the artifact. For scm we might be able to assume all scm revision numbers less than the one stored on the artifact are ancestors.
3. With the information from 1 and 2 determine the commits for the artifact being deployed in the environment in EnvironmentComponentEventListener. We would have to correlate the component version with the artifact version for now until a more flexible association mechanism can be devised.

}
```
- Modified /artifacts rest API endpoint slightly to accept a map of metadata
- Code that makes use of artifacts was updated to grab build information as needed by correlating jobUrl, instanceUrl, and buildNumber
- Jenkins plugin updated to work with api changes

This change allows for an independent artifact collector to be created. It also allows artifacts data to be inserted into the database before build data has been collected. Example curl to perform:

```
curl -X POST http://myapiendpoint:8080/api/artifact -H 'Content-Type: application/json' --data \
"{ \"artifactName\": \"Helloworld\", \"canonicalName\": \"Helloworld\", \"artifactGroup\": \"mygroup\", \"artifactVersion\": \"$projectVersion\", \"timestamp\": $(date +%s%3N), \"metadata\": { \"buildUrl\": \"$BUILD_URL\", \"buildNumber\" : $BUILD_NUMBER, \"jobName\": \"$JOB_NAME\", \"jobUrl\": \"$JOB_URL\", \"instanceUrl\": \"$JENKINS_URL\" } }"
```

Code added from #830:
The following metadata is now published with the jenkins plugin

scmUrl
scmBranch
scmRevisionNumber
column5: Reduce coupling between artifacts and builds collections

column2:
When you do a `mvn clean install`, there are TONS of info-level and debug-level messages. Most of the time, you're really only ever looking for warn-level and error-level messages. This makes it hard to tell if anything out of the ordinary happened during a build (and it's a heck of a lot of text to try and parse through).

Even running maven in quiet-mode (i.e. `mvn clean install -q`) doesn't work completely - the source of the problem seems to stem from each application's logging configuration. Ideally, you'd give maven a command-line arg to increase the verbosity of a build (maybe only for Travis builds and if you're actually interested in info/error-level messages for something). By default, the amount of messages displayed during a build would be kept to an absolute minimum.

Thoughts?

I think I've gotten this working on a previous project just by changing configurations for logback, etc., so I could give it a shot if you guys think it's a good idea.

column2:
The current model for a Binary Artifact is:

```
{
    "_id" : ObjectId("57d2c61646e0fb000d3ef42d"),
    "_class" : "com.capitalone.dashboard.model.BinaryArtifact",
    "timestamp" : NumberLong(0),
    "artifactName" : "Helloworld",
    "canonicalName" : "Helloworld",
    "artifactGroupId" : "mygroup",
    "artifactVersion" : "myversion",
    "buildInfo" : {
        "_id" : ObjectId("57d2c6014cedfd0018e051e9"),
        "collectorItemId" : ObjectId("57d15681d601800018b4e626"),
        ...
   }
}
```

where buildInfo is a duplicate of what would exist in the build collection. At present buildInfo is populated by BinaryArtifactService by using a String representing an ObjectID that is passed in to the /artifact rest API endpoint.

This model requires a build to already exist in the database by the time artifact data is populated. It is also redundant. The result of this coupling prevents an artifact collector from being feasible as there wouldn't be a reasonable way to coordinate it with an independent build collector.

I propose that the BinaryArtifact document be changed to look something like this:

```
{
    "_id" : ObjectId("57d2c61646e0fb000d3ef42d"),
    "_class" : "com.capitalone.dashboard.model.BinaryArtifact",
    "timestamp" : NumberLong(0),
    "artifactName" : "Helloworld",
    "canonicalName" : "Helloworld",
    "artifactGroupId" : "mygroup",
    "artifactVersion" : "myversion",
    "buildData" : {
        "buildNumber" : 140
        "buildUrl" : "mybuildurl/job/etc"
   }
}
```

Code that needs to relate artifacts to builds can still do so by using buildUrl + buildNumber as a composite key to search for a unique build in the builds collection. This loosens the coupling allowing for artifact information and build information to be pulled independently of eachother. As a result an artifact collector could be created in the future (note that the artifacts would have to have metadata to associate them to builds such as artifactory properties).
